    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05-14_page01.jpg"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#North-Audley-Street-1_ENK">1 North Audley Street No longer</placeName>
                        <date when="1841-05-14">Riegate - ten oclock clock Friday night May 14<hi rend="superscript">h</hi> 1841</date></dateline>
                 
                </opener>
                <p>
                
                    My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is<lb/>
                    here safe and sound and <choice>
                        <orig>com<lb/>
                            fortably</orig>
                        <reg>comfortably</reg>
                    </choice>
                    in bed in a very good<lb/>
                    mattress - and her head as low<lb/>
                    as she likes -- All right -- and<lb/>
                    she has had tea &amp; eaten bread<lb/>
                    &amp; butter &amp; a bit of <hi rend="underline">dry</hi> toast nicely<lb/>
                    buttered by no hands as you<lb/>
                    may guess but those of Blackly-<lb/>
                    -black &amp; Kindly-kind - To be<lb/>
                    sure Lestock is the fondest &amp;<lb/>
                    most tender of husbands &amp; <choice>
                        <orig>con-<lb/>
                            stantly</orig>
                        <reg>constantly</reg>
                    </choice>
                    <add>gentle to <hi rend="underline">her</hi></add> - But that is not what<lb/>
                    I was going to say - or you<lb/>
                    wanting to know <add>(You impatient people <lb/>
                    I see and I hear you!)</add><lb/>
                   </p>
                   <p>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is not nearly as<lb/>
                    much tired as I feared and<lb/>
                    I am sure as you feared she<lb/>
                    would be --- Perhaps however<lb/>
                    the bruise of tiredness may not<lb/>
                    appear immediately &amp; I must<lb/>
                    wait till I see how she is in<lb/>
                    the morning -- However you<lb/>
                
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05-14_page02.jpg"/>
                    may as well have the pleasure<lb/>
                    of this good report while it<lb/>
                    is fresh &amp; true - <lb/></p>
                
                <p>
                    We left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> about five &amp;<lb/>
                    twenty minutes before six<lb/>
                    and were here a quarter<lb/>
                    before 9 - three and twenty<lb/>
                    miles- - not quite half way<lb/>
                    to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Brighton_ENK">Brighton</placeName> - seven and twenty<lb/>
                    miles further to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Brighton_ENK">Brighton</placeName><lb/>
                    <del></del> So we cannot yet look<lb/>
                    back on the hardest part &amp;<lb/>
                    laugh - But we did smile<lb/>
                    often on the way hither, for<lb/>
                    it was a very good smooth<lb/>
                    road - one long hill to go<lb/>
                    down excepted she did not<lb/>
                    feel any inconvenience but<lb/>
                    the downhill motion pains<lb/> </p>
                
                <p>
                    - The evening was delightful<lb/>
                    and all the air perfumed<lb/>
                    (too much for her taste) with<lb/>
                    hawthorn and lilacs &amp;<lb/>
                    laburnams &amp; Judas trees in<lb/>
                    such full flower &amp; horse <choice>
                        <orig>ches<lb/>
                            nuts </orig>
                        <reg>chesnuts</reg>
                    </choice>
                    in such full candalabra<lb/>
                    beauty - as she lay in the<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05-14_page03.jpg"/>
                carriage she could see some<lb/>
                    of these <del>and</del>her dear cheerful<lb/>
                    ready to be pleased temper<lb/>
                    is charming!<lb/> - </p>
                
               <p>
                   <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">Lestock</persName> had contrived her<lb/>
                   diagonal couch so that<lb/>
                   she lay almost at full length<lb/>
                   her legs just humoring the<lb/>
                   thing. <figure></figure> "Je renonce a Ã§a"<lb/>
                   This part my <lb/>
                   skill to foreshorten <lb/>
                   myself and therefore I must<lb/>
                   leave that square with M, <add>a black blot</add> to <choice>
                       <orig>repre-<lb/>
                           sent </orig>
                       <reg>represent</reg>
                   </choice>
                   <del>both</del> my seat &amp; myself-<lb/>
                   I am sorry to have made <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">Lestock</persName><lb/>
                   such a dumpy man -<lb/>
                   - But you may comprehend<lb/>
                   by these Scribbloglyphics <lb/>
                   how we sat- tho not what like we were -<lb/>
                   Tell <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FranX1">Dr Francis</persName> that the case wh <hi rend="superscript">h</hi><lb/>
                   he had made for my writing<lb/>
                   &amp; dressing &amp; work-box made<lb/>
                   my seat standing on end &amp; put<lb/>
                   in a green-baize-bag &amp; with<lb/>
                   a horse hair cushion <add>at tuppence</add> for me<lb/>
                   to sit upon- Oh! exactly the<lb/>
                   thing! <del>&amp;</del> I had it made the day<lb/>
                   before by a charming man I went &amp;<lb/>
                   <unclear>preached</unclear> to and <hi rend="underline">prayed</hi> to about it in<lb/>
                   <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Oxford-Street-ENK">Oxford S <hi rend="superscript">t</hi> </placeName>- <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> directed me to<lb/>
                   him and he is <hi rend="underline">impayable</hi> but I paid him - &amp; only 3/6<lb/>
 
                
                   <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05-14_page04.jpg"/>
                   It was thought impossible that<lb/>
                   I could be squeezed into the<lb/>
                   carriage and so it would,<lb/>
                   have been, <hi rend="underline">but</hi> for this device<lb/>
                   &amp; this darling <del>box of</del> Case of -<lb/>
                   cases - never sat so comfortably<lb/>
                   <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">FMWs</persName> <add>writing</add> Box for footstool &amp; all!<lb/> </p>
                
                <p>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxB1">Barry</persName> joins us tomorrow<lb/>
                    by 3 o clock - waits till letters<lb/>
                    come in in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> at 10 o clock<lb/>
                    in hopes of hearing from <hi rend="underline">HB</hi><lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">his</hi> HB - And when I know <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet Butlers</persName>
                    intentions as to coming I can settle<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">mine</hi> as to going &amp; will <hi rend="underline">let you</hi> know<lb/>
                    We go to Hotel at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Brighton_ENK">Brighton</placeName> first<lb/>
                    day, while <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxB1">Barry</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">Lestock</persName><lb/>
                    house=hunt - The gentle <choice>
                        <orig>Giant<lb/>
                            -ess,</orig>
                        <reg>Giantess</reg>
                    </choice>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">Mary</persName> , is with us - came with<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtJ1">John</persName> the best of Johns <del>(except</del><lb/>
                    (<hi rend="underline">King John</hi> , <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">(Lucy)</persName> always excepted<lb/>
                    for your sake) <lb/></p>
                
                <p>
                    - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RossX1">Ross</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LeweX1">Lewen</persName> will<lb/>
                    come on Morrow to us &amp; then<lb/>
                    we shall be ourselves again<lb/>
                    with all our <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#North-Audley-Street-1_ENK">North Audley</placeName><lb/>
                    comforts full upon us<lb/>
                    and I hope to be able <hi rend="underline">to give</hi><lb/>
                    you a good <add>acct</add> of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> tomorrow<lb/>
                </p>
                
             <p>
                    Good bye now dearest<lb/>
                   <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> - I hope this will <hi rend="underline">still</hi><lb/>
                    your anxiety, which I know<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">must</hi> be very great ) 
                    at a <hi rend="underline">distance!</hi> when even<lb/>
                    mine on the spot was great enough<lb/>
                     your affec<lb/>
                <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria E</persName><lb/>
                </p>
           
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
